MADRID, March 28 (Reuters) - Spain will meet the goal of spending 2% of its economic output in defense as requested by NATO within a multi-annual period, Spain's Prime Minister said on Monday. "Spain will meet its 2% defense spending target within a multi-annual period," he said on Monday. NATO member countries have committed to defense spending at 2 percent of GDP. Several European countries, including Germany, Poland and Denmark, have increased military spending in response to the Ukraine crisis. Our Standards: The Thomson Reuters Trust Principles.